<section class="page-head">
  <div class="breadcrumb">
    <a href="<%= rel_root %>index.html">Registry</a> /
    <span>Divergence leaderboard</span>
  </div>
  <h1>Divergence leaderboard</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    The top 20 terms with the most distinct definitions across the publications that use them.
    A high count here is a strong signal that the term needs editorial harmonisation.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <table class="leaderboard-table">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>#</th>
        <th>Term</th>
        <th>Vocabulary</th>
        <th>Instances</th>
        <th>Distinct definitions</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
    <% dataset.leaderboard(20).each_with_index do |t, i| %>
      <tr>
        <td class="num"><%= i + 1 %></td>
        <td><a href="<%= rel_root %><%= t.path %>"><%= h t.name %></a></td>
        <td><%= kind_badge(t) %></td>
        <td class="num"><%= t.publications.size %></td>
        <td class="num"><span class="divergence-count"><%= t.distinct_definitions.size %></span></td>
      </tr>
    <% end %>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</section>

<section class="card note">
  <h2>How "divergence" is measured here</h2>
  <p>
    Today, divergence counts <em>distinct verbatim definitions</em>. Two
    publications may use the same words and rank as non-divergent, even
    when one adds or drops a clause. The AI consistency check
    (<code>scripts/check_consistency.rb</code>) provides a semantic
    comparison against the official VIM/VIML definition, surfacing
    <code>ok</code> / <code>partial</code> / <code>ko</code> per instance;
    once that has been run, this leaderboard can be retitled to surface
    semantic drift instead.
  </p>
</section>
